                <head>No. 168.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Bayard</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Denby</persName>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1887-05-03">
                            <hi rend="italic">May</hi> 3, 1887</date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 193.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have received and read with much interest your
                    dispatch No. 328, of March 8 last, concerning the article by the Marquis Tseng,
                    entitled “China: the Sleep and the Awakening,” published in the Asiatic Monthly
                    Review.</p>
                <p>It is encouraging to see so astute an observer as the Marquis Tseng pay so high a
                    tribute to the friendly and just disposition of the United States toward China
                    and our firm respect for international obligations and comity.</p>
                <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">T. F. Bayard.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
